animal.description:
Meet Junie! This 3/4 month mixer is just a roly poly fun loving dumpling! He is very dog friendly and loves to Dino and play. When he was abondibed at acct Philly he was sent to rescue for resource guarding. This sweetie was so insecure he’s even guard his water. But after a month of training here with us he is free feeding and sharing toys with all! He’s a very smart trainable Pip with plenty of energy to burn and lots of cuddles to give!

Return answered Questions/details with pics of home!
Basic
1. Full name of all household members and ages
2. Address 
3. Phone number
4. Email address

Key questions
1. are you willing to housebreak a dog? 
2. are you willing to work with a professional trainer and behavioral issues ever arise that are out of your wheelhouse before considering re-surrendering the dog to the rescue? 
3. do you understand that transitioning 
 a dog can result in behavioral issues such as pacing inappropriate elimination growling chewing defensive behavior aggressive behavior depressed behavior and that each dog will need a unique amount of time to adjust?
4. Are all the current pets in your home up-to-date on rabies? 
5. are you willing to join  our private Facebook group forever family to keep in touch and share photos?

Learn about you questions

1. Do you have children in the home? What ages?
2. What other animals live in the home?
3. Do you have a fenced in yard?
4. Do you own or rent? City suburbs or other?
5. What’s your family’s energy level? how would you describe your lifestyle?
6. What type of dog do you picture yourself with?
7. What do you consider the most important behaviors or characteristics in a dog you adopt?

Details
Hey there! Are you interested in a pup? All our dogs are dog friendly, kid friendly, and can be cat tested. They will be UTD medically and may have required return visits for more vet care based on their needs.
Puppies are $1000/dogs are $800
Spay neuter
Microchip
Rabies*1
Distemper* 1-4 
Lepto* 2
Bordetella if desired
Heartworm test-pets over 6 months
Health cert 
Fecal exam
Deworming unlimited until negative fecal 
Current on :Flea tick prevention and Heartworm prevention 
Starter food
Treats
Toy
Poop bag dispenser
30-45 min training session at your local petsmart
Exclusive petsmart Coupons including free over night stay in hotel and doggie day camp visit. 30% off first groom too! 
Access to Furever Family private fb group
*Collar Leash - if available 
Seasonal extras

Please note there is a $25 cancellation fee. We ONLY set up meets with aproved adopters. Also, we do not "hold" dogs for any length of time once an application is approved (example: vacations, moving, travel). Please only apply if you are truly ready *now* to bring a new dog into your home. If you come out for your meet, unless it is not a fit, expect to take your pet and supply package home to start your in home trial. 
If you do make an appt for a private meet and do not select a pet, a fee of $25 -30 mins or $50 - over 30 mins will apply for your private visit. 

To adopt contact  Furever2016@gmail.com 
To get started send in pictures of your home and outdoor space. You will receive an application and a telephone interview. Then it’s time to meet our pets at their foster home- often in Ambler. On that day you will meet your pet and take them home for an in-home trial period. Just to make sure it’s a great fit for everyone! We require each adopter to join our private Facebook group Furever Family to keep in touch!

animal.description:
This handsome boy is Cody, a 2 year old Husky mix.  Cody is super friendly, loves people, gets along with both big and small dogs.  NO cats, NO Chickens.  Cody is housebroken and can be crated, likes car rides and LOVES walks.  Like most Huskies he is very energetic and will have to have a  fenced yard and a family that can give him lots of attention and playtime. He also loves to just sit and chill out after a nice long walk.  He will sit on command and has quite nice manners.  He does pull some on a leash so a walking harness is recommended.  Cody will be a fabulous dog for an active, energetic pet owner. His adoption fee is $250. Located in Springfield, Mo, 

To find out more please fill out an application at www.wonderweimsrescue.com/adoptable-dogs/. To speak with the foster or visit the adoptable pet you must have an approved application on file.   Once you fill out an application a volunteer will contact you to get you approved.  Also check us out on facebook - http://www.facebook.com/wonderweimsrescue.

animal.description: Woof, woof! I'm so excited you're thinking about adopting a new fur-ever family member! Here are a few things that may help you with your big decision. First, dogs just want to be happy and feel loved. Living inside and being a part of the family is really important to us. A lot of the things you need as humans to stay happy and healthy, us dogs need too. We depend on you for things like vet visits, nutritious food, clean water, social and play time with people and other pets, training classes, toys, and of course, lots of love and attention! Regular baths, nail trims and grooming help us to look and feel our best, while monthly flea and heartworm prevention help us to stay healthy. Did you know that depending on our size and breed, dogs can live up to 20 years? Just think of the wonderful life we could have together!

No marathons for this guy, unless they're on Netflix! Ask about how you can help this special senior today!

animal.description:
Hi, everyone. I'm very shy so as my foster mom writes this, I have my head hidden under her bed. My name is Rebel which I must have been named ironically. I am a timid, but very sweet and smart 4year old lab/hound mix, weighing in around 45-50 lbs. I am slow to warm up to new people but I love snuggling with my people once I'm very familiar with them. When my family has friends over, I can be found hiding in a back bedroom until the friends leave. When I meet new dogs, however, I am very excited and friendly, showing my more playful side. I have even done fine around cats and chickens so far. I also LOVE being outside, running and hopping around the yard.
My foster family says I am very good about doing my business outside, going into my kennel, and behaving nicely when I'm left to roam the house when they are gone. It has taken me quite a while to feel comfortable around my foster family, but with patience and kindness, I now eat, drink, go potty, and occasionally venture out of my resting spots to be near my people. It will very likely take some time to grow comfortable with my forever family, but I promise it will be worth it. You will find me a very loving, sweet, and mostly mellow pup with a playful, gentle soul.
Bonus: I am up to date with shots, spayed, and microchips which makes me a steal for my adoption fee of $300. I will make a wonderful addition to any person's/family's life if they have the patience to give me the time to open up and feel comfortable in your home so I can show you what a fantastic companion I can be. I am being fostered in Viroqua, WI. If you'd like to consider adopting me, please apply at http://www.lastpawrescue.org/
501(c) approved WI agricultural license 285589 DS

animal.description:
Watch out world up for debut are the Hamilton County Parks Litter 
These 10 amazing 4-6 pound lab/boxer puppies are 8 weeks old and ready for their furever homes.  They are working on using their puppy pads, they love to play with their stuffed animals (crinkle, squeaky), & love to cuddle and take naps.  They have been fostered with kittens and a young dog. Dad was noted as being a boxer and mom is noted as being a lab.  These babies will melt your hearts. Their adoption fee is $400.00

Campbell Lakes "Campbell", male
He is one of the sweetest of the bunch.  he loves cuddles and has the most endearing look in his eyes.  His ears perk up when he is spoken to and his tail goes wild. Campbell's adoption fee is $400


To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

animal.description:
PHOTOS:  Virtually all of our dogs have online PHOTO ALBUMS through SmugMug with LOTS of additional pictures.  Just copy and paste the link below into your browser (or simply type it in) and then search for the dog's "gallery" by name

          http://adoptasleddog.smugmug.com

VIDEOS:  In addition to photo albums, almost every dog has a video which will give you a much better "feel" for his or her personality.  NOTE:  In the new Petfinder format, it has become quite a bit more difficult to find and to play videos.  Please PAGE THROUGH the photos, looking for a photo overlaid in the center with a "play" arrow inside a circle.  This icon is white, so it can be difficult to see. 
 In many (most) cases, the video is the last photo displayed as you page through.  Just click on that photo and it will play.  Please make sure you CHECK ON THE PETFINDER VIDEO ICON, above, to see a video of this wonderful dog!  Our videos will include, at a minimum, whatever info we had on the dog upon (or shortly after) his/her arrival into our program.  There will sometimes be video updates as well.  And in every case, our Adoptions Coordinator can be emailed at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to answer questions and provide the most current information we have on the dog.  

NOTES:  Please see video or contact our Adoptions Coordinator at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM.

ADOPTION DONATION:  $250  Before adoption, all Northern Lights dogs (regardless of whether Petfinder's symbols appear) are spayed or neutered, microchipped, heartworm negative, fully vaccinated and tested/treated for known parasites.
 
WHAT TO DO IF YOU WANT TO ADOPT THIS DOG:  Email us at ADOPTASLEDDOG@AOL.COM to request an application and get started.  WE DO NOT HAVE AN ONLINE APPLICATION - you will have to request one via email.  We will review your application to determine if there is a good fit between you and/or your family and this dog.  We may suggest another dog or dog(s) if we can offer a better fit in terms of lifestyle, experience, other pets, etc.  A vet check, reference checks, and a home visit will be conducted before an adoption can be considered for approval.  
 
NORTHERN LIGHTS DOES NOT HAVE A PHYSICAL SHELTER.  We are a nonprofit rescue organization comprised of individuals who open their private homes to foster dogs in need of a second chance..  When fosters are not available, we often pay to board a dog until space is available.  New fosters and donations to pay for boarding are always desperately needed us.  Email us at KATYLIED2@AOL.COM if you are interested in donating or for information on fostering.
 
FAQ:  For information regarding our organization, as well as adoption policies and practices, please visit our Petfinder Home Page at WWW.NORTHERNLIGHTS.PETFINDER.COM.
 
 
NOTICE:  In the vast majority of cases, the dogs in our program and rescued from shelters, and Northern Lights has no means by which to collect or verify a dog's history.  We work in concert with our veterinarians, and breed and age estimates are based on a combination of professional input and our collective experience.  Our policy with information acquired prior to acceptance and while the dogs are in our care is that of "full disclosure".  It is our goal to ensure the adopter has all available information to ensure the best possible match between the dog and the adopter(s).  If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

Meet Biden! This sweet boy is new to Gateway Pet Guardians. So far we know that he is about 2 years old and weighs 55 lbs and has been good around people and other dogs.

If you're interested in meeting Biden, please visit our website to learn about our adoption process and to fill out an application, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

All of our dogs and cats will be micro-chipped, spayed or neutered, and up-to-date on vaccinations at the time of adoption. For more photos of Biden, follow us on Facebook Gateway Pet Guardians and Instagram @gatewaypets ... #gpgBiden. 

To view other adoptable pets from our shelter, please visit, www.gatewaypets.org/adopt

Gateway Pet Guardians is proud to offer a variety of mixed breed dogs available for adoption. However, please keep in mind that we rarely know the genetic background of the animals we rescue and, as such, we cannot guarantee the exact breed combinations found within this dog. However, we do not know his/her actual genetic makeup. Just know that this dog is probably a variety of several different breeds that have combined to create one very amazing and unique animal.

animal.description:
**Please read Remi's entire profile, which includes a link to the adoption application. Thank you!** 

Meet Remi, a 9-month old, 40-pound Mountain Cur/Box mix young fellow in need of a friend.

Remi is a sweet young boy.  He loves people and just wants to be loved. 

He is shy and needs more socialization, but this will be easy in a home where he is treated like family. He's at a good age to train and incorporate into your home.  

How can you resist those bright sweet eyes! 

All dogs are up to date on vaccinations and spayed/neutered at the time of adoption.  All dogs require professional training to become the best family member they can be.

To adopt or learn more about Remi, you must fill out an adoption application. To find the application, copy and paste this URL into your browser: WWW.GDRNE.COM/ADOPTION-APPLICATION [Adoption Fee: $495]  **  PLEASE READ: If a dog is listed, then s/he is currently available for adoption. Their information is correct to the best of our abilities and the information we have been given as of the day of posting. Please note, GDRNE does not guarantee the breed of any dog or puppy unless stated that we have run DNA. All breeds listed are educated estimates. Our dogs are rescued from various situations. It is most likely that both their parents were strays and even if not, mixes of some sort and that their grandparents were mixes as well. The dog may have some genetic material of an American Staffordshire Terrier (pit bull). The dogs are usually mixes of many breeds, making them a breed all their own - a True and adorable American MUTT. If you are interested in this dog, you must submit an application. Great Dog is not a shelter so there is no building you can visit. Our dogs live in private foster homes until adopted. To learn more about our *shelterless* rescue, adoption fees, and procedures, review the list of Frequently Asked Questions on our website at WWW.GDRNE.COM.

animal.description:
Courtesy Listing

Dyllan is a nine year old neutered male boxer mix. He is well behaved, great with children, very patient and calm. He loves playing and being around other dogs of any breed. His last companion was a very small chihuahua. He would do better with a dog of similar age. He does well with cats, mostly just stays away from them. He loves attention from all humans and really is needing someone to spend more time with him. He is an inside dog and doesn't like being out in the yard alone but enjoys being outside with his people. He won't swim but will go in the water up to his chest. He loves to play and go for walks. If you are interested in adopting Dyllan, please complete an online application at lsar.org

If we have identified a behavioral or health condition while the dog is in our care and custody, every effort will be made to correct it prior to adoption, OR the adopter will be made aware of the issue or condition prior to adoption.  Northern Lights' screening process is designed to identify only those adopters who are willing, and have the means, to treat conditions which may occur after adoption, and the adopter will be contractually responsible for doing so. However, Northern Lights' policy is to accept any adopted dog back into the program, at any time, for any reason.

animal.description:
Guinness is currently living in a foster home. Please submit an application and we will link you up for an intro!

Guinness is eligible for a foster-to-adopt.

Age: ~ 1 year
Weight: ~75lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Yes, doing well with his crate training 
Dog sociability: is a frustrated greeter on leash (will bark/pull/jump when he sees other dogs), has done well off leash in playgroup with other dogs
Cat sociability: not a match
Kid compatibility: not a match (stranger danger)
Ideal living situation: Adult-only home in a quiet neighborhood. No high-rises or large apartment buildings

Guinness is the smartest dog ever! He loves to interact with you and will try to spend as much time as possible with you. He is super inquisitive and will follow you all over the house just to see what you're up too. Guinness loves his routines and insists on a bite of cheese first thing in the morning before you get your coffee and wants to say good night every night at bed time. Guinness does have some challenges with taking walks and meeting new people and is looking for an adopter that can continue his training plan. Once he gets to know you, he loves you fiercely! As a German Shepard Dog training is the name of the game. If you like teaching dogs new skills and keeping existing ones sharp he is your guy! Guinness needs space to stretch his long legs and get in some good vigorous play with a ball or stick so having a back yard is a plus for him. He will thrive in a quiet neighborhood as well. This good boy is so ready to find his home!

Due to a generous donation his adoption fee is now sponsored and he is neutered, up to date on vaccinations, heartworm tested and microchipped.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
lap Jack is a 3 year old Pyr mix looking for his forever home.  He loves all dogs, but plays hard, so dogs who love that would be a great partner for Flap Jack.  He is a dog who would love to have an active family (walks, runs, hikes) and the will settle down with some belly rubs as you stream sports or movies.  If you would like to learn more about Flap Jack, please complete an application and then reach out to Mandy@bigfluffydogs.com

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please apply online, at https://bigfluffydogs.com/adopt/adoption-application/. 

Our main website, www.bigfluffydogs.com has more information about us and the rescue process. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters should understand that each home is different and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for 1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (i.e. a 4-month-old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break). 2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise. 3.) Socialization.  The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home. 4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded ten-fold, for years to come.  Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy.  Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time-consuming and can be expensive. All dogs require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well trained, well-socialized dog is more than worth the effort to get them there.

Scout is super eager to please his people and is doing well learning his basic commands through positive reinforcement. We do not know a ton of his history, but Scout is very excitable and would do best in a home without small children or cats. At this time we are unsure how he would do with another dog in the home. Scout is more than happy to curl up and ask for belly rubs...but he prefers a nice long walk first to get all his sillys' out! Scout wants everyone to know he sees the world through rose-coloured glasses, even if its just with his one eye!

***We've made changes to our adoption process. To adopt:
1. View Scout's profile: spca.bc.ca
2. Submit an application: https://spca.bc.ca/survey/cat-adoption-application-nanaimo
3. If it's a match, staff will contact you to set-up an appointment to come in for a visit or virtual meet & greet!
4. Live happily furever after
***We often receive many applications for an available animal. We do our best to respond, although are not always able to respond to all applicants. We will reach out to the approved adopter Primary Color: Red Weight: 35.9kg Age: 0yrs 8mths 1wks Animal has been Neutered

animal.description:
Wolfie has been gaining weight with a wonderful foster and is now eligible for adoption! Wolfie was used as a breeding dog to produce pretty puppies before she ended up at a rural animal shelter. She's had a rough time but her spirit is strong! She acts like a puppy for a dog her age and she's ready to find a home!

Wolfie is an indoor pup that is crate-trained, good in the car, house-broken and very dog friendly. She will whine or howl to go outside (which sometimes may be 2AM but hey! She doesn't want to have an accident ).

She loves to groom other dogs and sleeps well in her crate. Wolfie doesn't dig and isn't a blanket chewer. Wolfie will scratch or bang on glass patio doors to be let in. She is a Husky and knows what she wants in life!

Wolfie has been seen by our veterinarian on staff. She is a 9 year old alaskan husky. She's been spayed, vaccinated, microchiped, dewormed and is up to date on all flea/tick prevention. She is heartworm negative and up to date on heartworm medication. To meet Wolfie, please check out our online adoption survey at http://www.secondchancenorman.com/index.php?survey

animal.description:
I am a senior dachshund boy and am around fifteen years-old. I'm very sweet to my foster mom, but can sometimes be a little cranky with other dogs if they get up in my face. For the most part, I get along fine with everyone though. I do enjoy sitting on the couch with foster mom and getting a good petting. I've just had a dental cleaning, so my breath is a lot better now. I lost several rotten teeth during the cleaning, so I'll need to eat soft food from here on out. I also had a benign fatty tumor removed from my side. It's healing up right now, but I might have a scar that makes me look extra fearsome! (Just kidding!) During the day and at night, I stay in my crate. I don't mind it in there at all as long as I have a nice comfy blanket to burrow under. I'm housebroken, but did mark a bit when I first went to my foster home. After a week or so, I didn't feel the need to do that anymore and have been perfect since. When let outside, I go potty right away and am sitting at the door ready to come back inside as soon as I'm done. There are no kids or cats here, so I can't tell you how I'd do with them. 
All in all, I'm a wonderful boy and would sure love to find my forever family. Could that be you?

animal.description:
I am a senior dachshund boy and am around thirteen years-old. Foster mom says I'm super sweet. I love to give kisses and snuggle up to my person on the couch. I've just had a dental cleaning, so my breath is a lot better now. However, I did lose a lot of rotten teeth, too, so I will need to eat soft food from here on out. During the day and at night, I stay in my crate. I don't mind it in there at all as long as I have a nice comfy blanket to burrow under. I'd also be more than happy to sleep in the bed with you if you're willing. I'm housebroken, but did mark a bit when I first went to my foster home. After a week or so, I didn't feel the need to do that anymore and have been perfect ever since. When let outside, I go potty right away and am sitting at the door ready to come back inside as I don't care for the cold weather. I get along fine with all the other dogs in the household, both big and small. There are no kids or cats here, so I can't tell you how I'd do with them. 
All in all, I'm a wonderful boy and would sure love to find my forever family. Could that be you?
If you would like to meet me, fill out an application and the Bella staff will arrange it.

Boo boo, along with her best friend Yogi, are looking for a potential adopter willing to open their home and heart to this lovely bonded pair. Boo boo is a sweet little cutie who can be apprehensive at first, but warms up quickly. Alongside Yogi, she is the gal that gives Yogi a confidence boost and helps him navigate around the world with a bit more comfort. She's able to give you an emotionally secure and mutually satisfying relationship. Boo boo is a bit more confident than Yogi when making friends with other dogs. She may be hesitant to approach other dogs at first, but with time and patience, she'll soon be initiating play. Let Boo boo sit at your feet, walk by your side, and she'll be forever thankful that you gave her and her best friend Yogi a chance.

If you're interested in learning more about Boo boo, along with her best friend Yogi, please email a completed application, found on our website, to Adoptions@eastbayspca.org; and mention the pair by name! Primary Color: Chocolate Weight: 9.22lbs Age: 0yrs 6mths 2wks Animal has been Spayed

animal.description:
Puddle is a female Lab Mix. She weighs just over 50 lbs. She is approximately 4 years old. She lived in a home with a family until they decided they didn’t want her anymore.  It’s a southern thing – when people get over a dog they don’t care what happens to the dog.  I agreed to take her in and never looked back.  She is an amazing girl.  She is happy go lucky and loves life. She does really well on the leash and is very smart.  She knows how to sit…..it takes a few times asking her but she does it.  So with treat training I think she would excel at training.  She is the perfect size for snuggling! A great girl to exercise with or cuddle with.  She loves to play fetch with the ball. She won’t give it back to you most times but loves to retrieve. For more info please let us know.

Adoption fees details: 
Puppies - Adults $ 550, Seniors $375. These adoption rates include transport from Alexandria, Louisiana to designated New England adopter pick up locations and NE foster homes using either Rescue Road Trips, Pets LLC or CAFA Transport. If you do a search you will see that this is a very reasonable adoption fee and comparable to other rescues. Adoption fee breakdown:Adoption Fee:   $  365.00Transportation Fee:  $ 185.00MA and NH only--Quarantine fee if applicable:  $125.00

Medical details:
All our dogs are altered (spayed or neutered), DHLPP, rabies, Bordetella, Heartworm tested with negative test results, microchipped, treated for parasites and on monthly heartworm and flea and tick prevention. A health certificate is issued by a licensed Louisiana veterinarian.

Adoption details:  
In some instances, a meet and greet is not possible before adoption unless we have a foster home in New England available. Available for a Meeting confirms the dog is in a NE Foster home and available for a meeting in the city state provided.  Most times our dogs get adopted before a foster home becomes available - and if so, they go straight to adopters home. Foster parents talk to adopters and feel confident that this will be a match before our dogs are transported up. Also if by some chance it is not a match we have a safety net in place as we ask that adopters to let us know that it is not a match and we direct you to take the dog to a foster home or boarding kennel once that is arranged. If necessary, we will ask you to foster the dog until a foster home can be arranged. 
Transport details:Rescue Road Trips (rescueroadtrips.com), Pets LLC (petsllc.net) or CAFA Transport will deliver our precious pups on commercial rescue animal transport to designated locations.  The fee is 185.00 which IS INCLUDED in your adoption fee already.**Rescue Road Trips, was featured on The Today Show - view it at http://www.today.com/video/today/55034556#55034556

MA and NH RESIDENTS:
If you are a Massachusetts or New Hampshire residence, an additional fee of $125.00 will apply due to State quarantine fee requirements. If the dog is in a foster home in MA or NH, this fee will be added in the adoption fee regardless of where the adopters home is located making the total adoption fee $675.00 for puppies and adults $500.00 for Seniors, otherwise the full adoption fee for all other states is $550.00 for puppies and adults and $375.00 for seniors. This includes a 48 quarantine, recheck by a MA licensed veterinarian, and issued a MA health certificate.

Visit all our available dogs at www.cenlaallianceforanimals.comWe update and add dogs frequently.

We hope to help make a difference in a rescue dogs life into loving responsible homes.

She loves to go lay on the couch or the bed and just chill. She is very inquisitive and always watches the birds and squirrels with her big beautiful brown eyes! She walks great on a leash and has never had a single accident in the house. She plays well with all 3 of my resident dogs, big and small. Seems to not care about the cats at all. animal.description:
Albert was found by a Good Samaritan who found him on the free next to a busy road. Thankfully, he sat down in the grass and Albert came over to him so he could save him.  He spent 5 days at a shelter waiting to be reclaimed, but no one came.  He is a young boy, about a year old, recently neutered and ready to go to a new home.  He is housebroken, knows basic commands such as sit, shake and down, and is comfortable going up and down stairs.  He loves romping with other dogs, and is okay with cats.  He's interested in them, but does not harm them. If they hiss and swat him, he backs up and barks.  We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Albert will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $400

animal.description:
Zoey is a sweet-faced senior with a perfect disposition. When her Caregiver was asked what her ideal home looks like, she said:

"I can see her curled up in a cozy lap or laps. I think she'd love to be the dog at a book club (quietly listening to the discussion from a variety of laps). Bonus if the home has a fireplace. She likes to stay warm and looks cute in sweaters if you like a well-dressed dog. She's happy to take your daily stroll or strolls with you, but it doesn't need to be far. Only dog? Dog friends? I don't think she's too picky on this point so long as there's lap to spare."

*Zoey takes a medication twice daily for a heart condition. Off the medication she had coughing, wheezing, and fainting spells. However, on the medication, she's been doing well and her symptoms are very well managed! She likes her walks and is active, but she shouldn't overexert herself.

animal.description:
I lived my life on this chain. 
The weight of the chain weighed heavily on my neck and heart. 
I paced in circles on the hole I created.
A mere few feet I could move.
The chain held me back and down.
I had no food to fill my belly.
I had no water to quench my thirst. 
My bowl was filled with dirt.
I had no family to love me and call my own.....
Just my life on a chain.
But this amazing rescue saved me, and showed me what is was like to be a dog. They gave me me a chance, I  thought would never come.
Since then I have been living with my foster family, who has been taken care of me, but now I’m ready to find my forever.

animal.description:
BEN is a 5 year old Yorkie who weighs 10 pounds.

He is a sweet and adorable boy who at times has a very sad and pensive side to him. He likes to go out for walks but definitely likes being inside more. Ben loves loves to sneak away and sleep on the bed. It's his favorite place to be and he is accustomed to sleeping in his foster mom's bed at night. Please be willing to allow him the same level of comfort. 

Ben has a great appetite and definitely lets you know he is hungry. He would do best in a home with a single human that doesn't have a huge social life as he craves attention and would like to be the center of your attention. Ben is more drawn to and more comfortable around women then men.

Ben suffers from chronic dry eye and will require eye drops 2x a day for the rest of his life which is fairly easy to administer. Ben could also use an understanding hand when it comes to housebreaking. While it has approved while in foster, it is certainly not perfect.

We do not adopt small dogs to homes with children and we do not adopt any dogs to homes with roommates. All meet and greets will be conducted close by his foster home in New York City. And due to Covid and inclement weather, we are only able to place him in Manhattan or Brooklyn at this time. 

To meet Ben please go to our website and fill out an application: www.beastlyrescue.org/application

animal.description:
Please welcome with wide open arms Miss Blossom!! 
This poor girl has had the worst luck from heartless people. No fault of her own!!
 
BLOSSOMS story will bring you to tears.
It all starts when she was picked up by animal control wandering a pregnant stray in our rescue areas of the rural mid south.
She was dumped at the pound waiting a scary fate being pit an prego. Only rescue could pull her put to safety.
Few days go by an 2 girls walk into that shelter looking to get a dog....
They pass her by in jail an they see her an tsay "hey Nola!" Shelter staff asks how they know her??
As Blossom is so excited to see them jumping up happy to see them.. 
they respond.."Oh that's our dog....but we don't want her anymore..." they walked away from Blossom standing there wagging hair tail at her mommy with all her hopes up... an then just shattered. 
The shelter staff told them to leave and that they will be getting no dogs! 
Could you imagine her heartbreaking???. I'm sure you could feel it around the world. 
Terrible just terrible.? Our team quickly saw her and pulled her out of deaths way an to safety awaiting our transport.
Soon after Blossom had her babies and she struggled with a very emotional labor and postpartum. This has been a tough road for this lady. 
We now have her in a loving Foster home an we will never fail her, she will never feel that heartbreak ever again. 
She is thriving with all the love and attention from her foster family. She is perfect!! She knows commends. Perfectly housebroken. Crate trained an is learning leash manners great. 
She is just a pocket pitty. Barely 40lbs. Little short stuff. We guess she is about 1/2 yrs old.  She doesn't mind kitties or dog meets. But she deserves to be the only dog in her new home. Let her get all the love no neglect anymore. 
Please come visit her in our awesome foster home. Come get to know her.
Email us for an application
Hemlockedgerescue@yahoo.com

animal.description:
Hi friend. My name is Chico and I'm a handsome Chihuahua searching for my furr-ever home. I'm a sweet boy looking for a patient family who will give me plenty of time to adjust. I'm a little shy around some people, so it may take me a little time to warm up to them. However, I am a super loving boy and I do well with most people with some encouragement. If I sound like a possible match for your family, please come in and see me! I'll be waiting.
HOW DID I COME INTO HHHS? I was brought in because my owner passed away, and was really shy. After coming to Helping Hands Humane Society I was placed into a foster home, and I'm now ready to find my fur-ever family. 
HEIGHT: 12" at the shoulder 
HOW MUCH EXERCISE DO I NEED? I enjoy laying around on the couch with my person. I still need some exercise though to keep me happy and healthy. 
DO I HAVE ANY SPECIAL TOYS? I do like to play with toys around the house. 
DO I KNOW ANY TRICKS? I would love to learn new tricks with my new family. 
AM I A GOOD INSIDE DOG? I would love to live inside so I can spend lots of quality time with you. I just need a patient family who will give me plenty of time to adjust. Please take me out to potty often, while I learn your routine. I get very excited when you come home and am always happy to greet you. Since I am past the puppy stage I'm very well behaved in the home. 
DO I LIKE CATS? I haven't been around any kitties yet. Please ask the adoption counselors to do a cat test with me before going home. 
DO I LIKE CHILDREN? I will do better with older children in the household, I won't be too overwhelmed. Like I said before, I'm a little shy around new people so just remember to go slow with me at first. 
DO I LIKE OTHER DOGS? I don't mind hanging out with other dogs. It would always be best to bring in any canine family members at home to meet with me before going home. 
Thanks for reading about me. If you are interested in me please ask an adoption counselor to set up a meet and greet. I can't wait!
Tail wags and kiss

animal.description:
Please meet Shelby!  She is a Pekingese/Papillon mix weighing in at 25 lbs of cuteness!  She and her fur siblings were owner surrendered to us in Bartlett, Tennessee. Their mom passed away and there was no one to care for them any longer.  She is a cute, feisty, fun little girl that loves friends, toys, walks, rides in the car and all kinds of attention. She is a typical Peke in that she can be very particular about things, especially having her face and ears messed with. She is more bluff than bite, but she doesn’t like being made to do things unless they are her idea. We absolutely adore her, but we want everyone to be aware that she does growl (many times we think it is more fun to her than seriousness) and we do not think she needs to live with children because of this. She is a complete lap dog and loves to be petted and have the attention. She would make the perfect dog for an older couple with a quiet household and lots of love to give. She would also make a great companion for anyone seeking a little lapdog that doesn’t expect too much out of her. We know this sounds like a difficult place and that she is a hard dog, but she really is the easiest dog in her foster home. She does her own thing and loves to just sit by you and snuggle. She is housebroken, crate trained (but does not require a crate) and walks very well on a leash. She is nervous about getting a leash put on over her head, but we do recommend a slip leash for her at all times, as she can get nervous about new things. She will require regular grooming, which we are trying to get her used to with daily brushings and trips to our groomer.  

If you are interested in this adorable, loving, young lady, please get your apps in as fast as you can!

THE APPLICATION LINK CAN BE FOUND ON OUR PETFINDER PAGE UNDER THE PICTURE. 


ANIMAL INFORMATION:  
Name:  Shelby 
Breed:  Pekingese/Papillon
Gender:  Female         
Age:  3 years      
Weight: 25 lbs           
Spayed/Neutered: Yes    
Vaccines: Current                      
Heartworm:  Tested negative on 1/5/2021, currently on Heartgard
Microchipped: Yes

FOSTER EVALUATION AND RECOMMENDATION:
Dogs:  Yes, fostering with dogs of various sizes, breeds and genders
Cats:  Unknown
Other Small Animals:  Unknown
Children:  Yes, older children. He has NOT been tested with infants or toddlers, so proper supervision and introductions would be required. 

ADOPTION INFORMATION:
We are a foster-based animal rescue and we thank you for your interest in one of our animals. Our animals are fostered in various locations in the a South and in New England. Our fosters and adoption coordinators are the backbone of what we do. Our fosters work tirelessly to integrate our rescue animals into their home, so that we can provide as much information to potential adopters as possible. In addition, our coordinators offer as much information regarding the medical and behavioral and personality characteristics as is known to our organization. Without them, and our extremely generous donors, we would not be able to save as many animals as we do every day. With each adoption, we operate a Pay It Forward program, whenever possible, to help other animals in our rescue and future animals in need. 

If you are interested in one of our animals, please complete an application. The application link can be found on our Petfinder homepage under the picture. You may also find our application on our website at www.petmatchmakerrescue.com under the Adopt page. If they are listed on our website, their adoptions have not been finalized yet. That does not mean that we have not received several applications, already. Please complete an application if you are interested and we will keep you apprised of their current status. We are all volunteers who work full-time jobs and have animals of our own, so please be patient with us. We will get back with you as quickly as possible.  

If you are interested in fostering for our organization, please complete an application.  The application link can be found on our Petfinder homepage under the picture.

From the Foster:

Virtubo has the sweetest temperament of all time! He is definitely a people-pleaser and loves to give and receive affection. He is potty trained and doing well in his crate, other than some initial whining. He does jump up when excited and give some "love chomps," especially when you come home from being gone all day or even just 5 minutes. He doesn't know many commands yet but seems to be a quick and eager learner.

Virtubo has muscles on top of muscles so he can easily knock you over or pull pretty hard on the leash when walking. He is currently living with a Husky, Pittie and a Chiwinnie. He and the Pittie are best friends and play all day. Virtubo does play a little rough since he is pretty strong but there hasn't been any issues because our dogs enjoy the rough play. It could be an issue if a dog does not like that type of play. He is very interested in our Chiwinnie and wants to play with her, but she wants nothing to do with that ball of muscle. When he does try to play with her, we redirect him, and he moves on. He can't help it though because he is just a happy guy that wants to play with everything.

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Jax. I'm a 4-year-old Treeing Walker Coonhound, weighing about 47-pounds. I was found running during hunting season, and my owner never came to claim me. I am looking for a home to help me break out of my shell! I'm a little nervous at first, but as long as you're calm and patient I'll warm up fast. I prefer older kids and adults since sometimes young kids move fast and really scare me! I love going on walks, getting pets, and napping on my foster mom's couch. My foster mom says I'd make a great hiking buddy, since I just want to explore and sniff everything every where we go! I also love playing with stuffed toys, and have done very well with other dogs, although I may be shy at first. I can't wait to find my forever home!

His adoption fee is $299. 

All Pet Central animals are up to date on age-appropriate vaccinations, spayed/neutered, micro-chipped (registration included), and current on parasite prevention. Dogs over six-months of age are heart-worm tested. When adopting, we will ensure that you receive copies of veterinary and microchip records. Due to the construction of our state of the art facility, none of our pets are on site, they are all located in foster homes at this time. 

If you are interested in this pet, please fill out the brief Adopter Survey by clicking on his profile.

After we review your completed survey we will contact you by phone or email within 72 hours or less. We're primarily a volunteer organization, so we appreciate your patience. Please note- Out of respect for our volunteers and staff, we are closed on Sundays and Mondays and will not be processing any applications on that day. Do get back to us right away when we call or email regarding an application so that we can quickly connect using the process below: - A PCH adoption counselor will contact potential adopters within three business days (PCH cannot guarantee any pets availability, but we make every effort to accommodate adopters with a reply and possible alternative suggestions). Counselor and client will then have a conversation to answer questions and determine the suitability of a match (if necessary, we may opt to put adopters in touch with foster parents via a meeting app). We do require that adopters discuss all questions before pickup via phone or email in order to minimize direct contact with our staff/volunteers at the time of adoption.

- After a match is made, clients will be asked to sign our adoption agreement and pay the **adoption fee through our secure website ***Please see our modified no-risk return policy
- We will promptly email all veterinary & microchip records.
- The PCH adoption counselor will then set up a specific appointment time to come to our office for drive-in pet pick up!
- Adopters should bring a pet carrier and leash to pick up. Adult pets will be wearing a collar. It is important that clients arrive on time, neither early nor late.
- Drive-in Curbside Cuddles adoption! Upon arrival inside the Crossroads Center complex (360 Wylie Drive), turn left and look for PCH signage in the corner, in front of the large blue "YouthBuild" sign on the building. Adopters should pull in the driveway and all the way up underneath the large overhang.
- Adopters must stay in their vehicle. Under no circumstances should clients exit their vehicle, so please be prepared with items such as blankets, paper towels, cleanup spray, garbage bags, etc. Call 309-846-9534 when ready.
- A PCH representative in protective gear will carry or walk the pet out and place in the client's vehicle. Social distancing practices should be respected during this process.
- We will take a "Happy Adoption Day" photo with family and new pet through the window of the vehicle. Thank you to all for saving the life of a shelter pet! **At this time, we can only accept online payment methods. We are unable to take cash and we do not accept checks. If you typically pay in cash please purchase a pre-paid credit card so you are able to use it to pay online! ***Adopter may return this animal for an exchange or refund within 14 days (Minus a $40 processing fee). This policy gives new families and their adopted pet time to get to know one another, as a temporary replacement for the usual face to face meeting with our staff and volunteers. Adopters are always encouraged to contact PCH post-adoption with any questions regarding behavior, health, etc. Our mission is to keep pets and their families happy and together if possible. Pet Central has experienced professionals available to help- from the initial adoption transition and throughout the lifetime of each pet! Thank you for considering a rescue pet!
Sincerely,
Pet Central

Name: Evan

Age: 2 years old

Gender: Male

Breed: Boxer Pointer Mix

Weight: 61 pounds

Dog friendly: Yes, with introductions

Cat friendly: unknown, testing available upon request

Child friendly: Yes, children ages 8+ years, please

House trained: Yes

Crate trained: Yes

Energy level: relaxed

Temperament: Timid and loving

Adoption Fee: $375+tax

To adopt, go to:

www.mendingspirits.org/apply-to-adopt.html

About Me: Hi, I'm Evan it is a pleasure to meet you! I came up from Alabama and really really like this white stuff that you humans call snow. I love to run and roll around in it as it feels so cool. I love playing with stuffed toys the best because I can throw them in the air and play catch with myself! I try to take everything that I think is a stuffed animal like my foster mom's boots and even blankets outside, but she catches me before I succeed. My mom tells me that I came from a bad place in the past and it makes it take a bit for me to warm up to humans. I am very curious about my new place and am not sure I can free roam so I stay close to the blanket I have on the floor. I have excellent potty manners and go outside to do my business. This crate thing she tries to put me in is a scary place and I would rather hang out on the couch to sleep at night. I love to cuddle with my mom and think that I am a lap dog, my mom tells me I am too big for that but I insist on trying because she eventually gives in. These walk things that my mom takes me on are also so much fun, I enjoy sniffing everything and also marking where we walked as well!! I am really hoping that I can find a furever home that will help me continue to become the most loving family dog I can be!

animal.description:
IMPORTANT: Please do not do an inquiry through Petfinder, our volunteers do not have time to reply to the inquiries. Please visit our website to learn more about our adoption process at newhoperescue.org. 

This dog is being fostered with New Hope Dog Rescue (Saskatoon).  If you are interested in adopting please fill out an Adoption Application. Meet and greets are by appointment only and done so after an adoption application has been submitted. A successful applications will be contacted by the foster home to discuss further. We are volunteer run so please be patient.
 

Hello!  My name is Nola.  I was born December 1, 2020.  I am a very happy and friendly little girl.  I love my cuddles and just playing/napping beside my human, or even just being in the same room on my blanket.   I absolutely LOVE toys – all kinds.  I love my rope, my stuffies and my balls, especially the treat balls.  And my foster mom says I am very smart – it only takes me a few minutes to figure out how the treat balls work (all 3 of them!).  I have lots of energy for a couple hours – and then I just flake right out for the next couple!  I also love the outdoors, especially the snow!  But I head for the door as soon as I get too cold!  I love laying on my blanket and will ‘fetch’ the toys my foster mom throws for me, for a long time; that’s a fun game.  
I am just a puppy so I know I have lots to learn.   I am getting very good at ‘sit’, but am working on the ‘stay’ part.  We used pee pads but now am starting to go outside; I have a special ‘spot’ to do my business and am getting very good at knowing what to do when I go there.  I do like to whine/bark a bit when I’m in my pen, sometimes for attention and sometimes when I’m playing, just to hear myself!   But I do not whine or bark when I’m in my kennel, whether that’s at night or during the day when my foster mom goes out.  I go a solid eight hours at night in my kennel  - I could likely go more but my foster mom needs to get up.  
I have lots of energy, so I would love a family with kids/pets or I would be very happy with an adult who likes getting out and playing. I have played with my foster’s grandson and we had so much fun!  And the visiting dog was very exciting; I shared my toys easily.   I am microchipped and shots up to date for my age.  I am available to be loved on Feb 5th.   I am just sooo ready for someone to love me; I have much love to give!  

Nola has been microchipped, dewormed, current on age appropriate vaccines and has received a health check from a vet. adoption fee is $495 (200 is refunded upon proof of spay).

To view more dogs go to http://www.newhoperescue.org/adopt/available-dogs/

Disclaimer: in most cases we are guessing the breed mix. These are best guesses on our part. For puppies it can be extremely difficult and we are also guessing on what size they will be. 

NEW HOPE DOG RESCUE is not a shelter. Our dogs are placed in loving foster homes. WE NEED FOSTER HOMES TO HELP MORE DOGS - CONTACT US TODAY!!!
Definitions:
Pending - means that we are working through the adoption process with the 1st applicant. We usually don't add the pending until we are pretty sure the adoption will go through (like at the home visit stage)
Adopted - you know!! A happy ending for a homeless dog.

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Wrigley. People call me "Wrigs" for short. I'm a 1-year-old, 50-pound Golden Retriever mix, and I'm adorable! I'm house-trained, crate-trained, and know some commands, too! I can sit, stay and shake! I learned those tricks when I was at puppy school. I'm in a home with children currently, and doing very well! I like to snuggle my human foster siblings and they are great at playing, too. I love to play in the snow, go on car rides, and play with my dinosaur toy! I'm looking for a home with a family to love me, play with me, give me lots of exercise and where there are no other small animals. I have been around other big dogs and do very well with them as long as they are my size- the small ones confuse me! Are they really even dogs? I will keep your yard free of cats and other small animals and give you all my love forever! Are you looking for a handsome boy like me? His adoption fee is $125. All Pet Central animals are up to date on age-appropriate vaccinations, spayed/neutered, micro-chipped (registration included), and current on parasite prevention. Dogs over six-months of age are heart-worm tested. When adopting, we will ensure that you receive copies of veterinary and microchip records. Due to the construction of our state of the art facility, none of our pets are on site, they are all located in foster homes at this time. If you are interested in this pet, please fill out the brief Adopter Survey by clicking on his profile. After we review your completed survey we will contact you by phone or email within 72 hours or less. We're primarily a volunteer organization, so we appreciate your patience. Please note- Out of respect for our volunteers and staff, we are closed on Sundays and Mondays and will not be processing any applications on that day. Do get back to us right away when we call or email regarding an application so that we can quickly connect using the process below: - A PCH adoption counselor will contact potential adopters within three business days (PCH cannot guarantee any pets availability, but we make every effort to accommodate adopters with a reply and possible alternative suggestions). Counselor and client will then have a conversation to answer questions and determine the suitability of a match (if necessary, we may opt to put adopters in touch with foster parents via a meeting app). We do require that adopters discuss all questions before pickup via phone or email in order to minimize direct contact with our staff/volunteers at the time of adoption.
- After a match is made, clients will be asked to sign our adoption agreement and pay the **adoption fee through our secure website ***Please see our modified no-risk return policy
- We will promptly email all veterinary & microchip records.
- The PCH adoption counselor will then set up a specific appointment time to come to our office for drive-in pet pick up!
- Adopters should bring a pet carrier and leash to pick up. Adult pets will be wearing a collar. It is important that clients arrive on time, neither early nor late.
- Drive-in Curbside Cuddles adoption! Upon arrival inside the Crossroads Center complex (360 Wylie Drive), turn left and look for PCH signage in the corner, in front of the large blue "YouthBuild" sign on the building. Adopters should pull in the driveway and all the way up underneath the large overhang.
- Adopters must stay in their vehicle. Under no circumstances should clients exit their vehicle, so please be prepared with items such as blankets, paper towels, cleanup spray, garbage bags, etc. Call 309-846-9534 when ready.
- A PCH representative in protective gear will carry or walk the pet out and place in the client's vehicle. Social distancing practices should be respected during this process.
- We will take a "Happy Adoption Day" photo with family and new pet through the window of the vehicle. Thank you to all for saving the life of a shelter pet! **At this time, we can only accept online payment methods. We are unable to take cash and we do not accept checks. If you typically pay in cash please purchase a pre-paid credit card so you are able to use it to pay online! ***Adopter may return this animal for an exchange or refund within 14 days (Minus a $40 processing fee). This policy gives new families and their adopted pet time to get to know one another, as a temporary replacement for the usual face to face meeting with our staff and volunteers. Adopters are always encouraged to contact PCH post-adoption with any questions regarding behavior, health, etc. Our mission is to keep pets and their families happy and together if possible. Pet Central has experienced professionals available to help- from the initial adoption transition and throughout the lifetime of each pet! Thank you for considering a rescue pet!
Sincerely,
Pet Central

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Lucky. I'm a 5-year-old Golden Retriever/German Shepherd mix weighing about 55-pounds. The name Lucky fits me because, well, I really am. I spent the first 5 years of my life pretty much living alone. I've likely never been pet before, or had the pleasure of knowing a loving human. It has taken me a little while to get use to people, and sometimes they still do really scare me, but I'm learning that people are pretty nice. I love the treats they bring me, and I am really starting to like those pets on my head. I haven't learned to cuddle yet, or to be pet extensively, but it is next on my list. I also want to learn that "sit and "walk on a leash trick I see my friends doing. I am a big boy (hey, it's muscles!) and need space to run. I don't know what these "cats are that people talk about, and I really haven't met many kids so I am not sure how I feel about those little humans. My dream home would be a very patient home, who doesn't mind if I take my time warming up to them and my environment. A home where I could learn how to be a dog, that people are nice, and pets feel good. So, if you are a farmer or just have lots of space and are looking for a very sweet redhead...I am your man!

His adoption fee is a donation of the adopters choice.

Counselor and client will then have a conversation to answer questions and determine the suitability of a match (if necessary, we may opt to put adopters in touch with foster parents via a meeting app). We do require that adopters discuss all questions before pickup via phone or email in order to minimize direct contact with our staff/volunteers at the time of adoption.
- After a match is made, clients will be asked to sign our adoption agreement and pay the **adoption fee through our secure website ***Please see our modified no-risk return policy
- We will promptly email all veterinary & microchip records.
- The PCH adoption counselor will then set up a specific appointment time to come to our office for drive-in pet pick up!
- Adopters should bring a pet carrier and leash to pick up. Adult pets will be wearing a collar. It is important that clients arrive on time, neither early nor late.
- Drive-in Curbside Cuddles adoption! Upon arrival inside the Crossroads Center complex (360 Wylie Drive), turn left and look for PCH signage in the corner, in front of the large blue "YouthBuild" sign on the building. Adopters should pull in the driveway and all the way up underneath the large overhang.
- Adopters must stay in their vehicle. Under no circumstances should clients exit their vehicle, so please be prepared with items such as blankets, paper towels, cleanup spray, garbage bags, etc. Call 309-846-9534 when ready.
- A PCH representative in protective gear will carry or walk the pet out and place in the client's vehicle. Social distancing practices should be respected during this process.
- We will take a "Happy Adoption Day" photo with family and new pet through the window of the vehicle. Thank you to all for saving the life of a shelter pet!

**At this time, we can only accept online payment methods. We are unable to take cash and we do not accept checks. If you typically pay in cash please purchase a pre-paid credit card so you are able to use it to pay online!

***Adopter may return this animal for an exchange or refund within 14 days (Minus a $40 processing fee). This policy gives new families and their adopted pet time to get to know one another, as a temporary replacement for the usual face to face meeting with our staff and volunteers. Adopters are always encouraged to contact PCH post-adoption with any questions regarding behavior, health, etc. Our mission is to keep pets and their families happy and together if possible. Pet Central has experienced professionals available to help- from the initial adoption transition and throughout the lifetime of each pet!

Thank you for considering a rescue pet!
Sincerely,
Pet Central

animal.breeds_label: Border Collie & Australian Cattle Dog / Blue Heeler Mix
animal.description:
Moe was a stray pup who found himself in a rural shelter surrounded by countless other dogs, who just like him, have never known what it is like to have a name. Moe is the name that we gave him, as he did not have one in the shelter. All of the dogs are known as, "Boy" or "Girl," and while this guy will never complain about staff calling him "Good Boy," he can't help but dream for the day he finds himself with a family who will give him a name he doesn't have to share with every other dog around him! Now Moe is with a foster, while he waits for his transport date to Colorado to find his forever home! Moe is super loving in his foster home. He loves going on walks, and playing with his foster doggy brothers! He is very social and loving.

Moe is likely a Border Collie/Cattle Dog mix, according to the vets. With almost any rescue though, breed is  just a guess! Moe is about 1 to 2 years old, and weighs 60 lbs. He is truly a gentle "giant", though he is not that big! 
?
With any rescue, moving from a shelter to a foster to an adoptive home can be very confusing. When an adopting family is sensitive to the challenges of change and acclimation for these dog's, the transition is far easier. A home with a very loving and nurturing family that understands that blossoming takes time would be perfect home for Moe. Socialization, pure love and belly rubs is a gift to a dog that is undergoing a life change. Given the time and space, these dogs shine. 
?
Farfel's Rescue has found over time (we've rescued more than 3,000 dogs over 15 years of rescue) that families that attend level 1 group training classes or address individual challenges at home with one of our approved positive reinforcement/force free trainers keep their dogs for life. Dogs that do not get proper training and socialization have a much higher risk of developing behavioral problems. There is a bonding that occurs through the training process that can't be duplicated. It also teaches behaviors that enable a dog to go out into the world with excellent manners that create a very respectful relationship between dogs and their humans. It is for all these reasons that Farfel's isn't willing to adopt to a family that doesn't choose to create this training relationship. Farfel's is happy to provide a list of approved positive reinforcement/ force-free trainers in your area. 
?
Moe is up to date on his shots, but has yet to be neutered. Farfel's will cover all costs of Moe's neuter! Neuter must be done within one month of adoption. Any adopter who adopts an unfixed dog will be legally considered a foster until the spay/neuter procedure is complete!
?
Moe is arriving on transport in Boulder on 2/10/2021. Applications are currently being accepted for our wonderful pup. If interested in this gorgeous, very cuddly/sweet and loving best friend, please fill out an application completely at http://farfels.com/farfels-rescue/adoption-form/ and submit.
?
**PLEASE NOTE** If you're truly interested in adopting from us, please be sure to fill out our Farfel's Rescue adoption application found at the link above or at farfels.com. Adoption site applications such as Petfinder, Rescueme and Adoptapet don't provide enough information and therefore aren't useful. Our Farfel's application is the only initial tool that we have to determine a great match for this very deserving puppy. We're sorry, but in most cases, we're unable to get back to those that don't submit our Farfel's Rescue adoption application. Thanks very much for choosing rescue.

animal.description: During the course of routine examination and treatment, your new pet was found to have Percussion abrasion on tail (Happy Tail) Treatment: Varies Special considerations or instructions: This dog has a common condition found in shelter dogs called happy tail. This results from the dog constantly wagging the tail and hitting the walls of a run. Some dogs, usually with shorter fur, wag their tails vigorously and repeatedly hit objects with the tip. The speed of the tail can result in a very hard impact on surfaces so that some dogs end up literally beating their tail bloody. Dog kennels are often narrow enough and dogs who orient towards people tend to spend their time standing in their kennel near the wall closest to the room's door so that they cannot avoid hitting their tail and causing bleeding. There is no universal treatment that works for every dog. Treatments include bandaging the tail and moving the dog to a bigger run. Fortunately, most dogs improve by leaving the shelter and living in a home. Most dogs in homes do not have this problem and any remaining wounds will heal in a home environment. A very few dogs continue to injure their tails in their new home. These dogs may require tail amputation to solve the problem. Fortunately, this is extremely rare.

animal.description:
Homer was a stray on the streets of Memphis like so many others but he was lucky in that he wandered right up to the house of someone who didn't ignore him. Some nice people took him in, gave him a bath, dinner and then they called a local rescue in the area.

Homeris settling in to his foster home and learning his new routine. This boy takes commands nicely - sit is his favorite!! So far he's doing well in his kennel and not doing his outside business inside! He's a medium energy, well behaved boy. He's learning leash walking as he pulls a bit.He may be a boy who gets car sick but we'll have to get back to you on that! 

He is being introduced to other dogs and doing well. We will post updates as we get to know this sweet guy!

Name: Homer
Sex: Male
Breed: Hound/Pit Bull Terrier
Age: 2 years estimate
Weight: 63
Spayed/Neutered: Yes
Vaccinations: Up to date
Heartworm: Positive, has started treatment.
Microchipped: Yes


BASED ON OUR OBSERVATIONS:
Good with Children: Unknown
Good with Dogs: Yes
Good with Cats: Unknown

Adoption Fee: $475.00

IMPORTANT INFORMATION:
Interested in a specific dog, please fill out an application if you are interested in a dog. The number of individual inquiries is overwhelming and we are finding it difficult to respond to each one. We cannot guarantee you will receive a timely response.

Paws New England is a rescue, not a shelter, and as such we do not have our dogs housed in one location - they are in foster homes both in New England and in our southern foster homes. If you're interested in a specific dog, please complete a short online application and you will receive a reply within 48 hours so you can ask questions.

At present, if a dog is listed on our website, the dog is considered still available HOWEVER, may have applications that have come in before yours but it's still too early to know if any are a good match; therefore we encourage you to apply.

NOTICE WITH REGARD TO LOCATION OF DOGS: Please note: Paws New England is a foster-based rescue. We do not have a brick and mortar building to house the dogs we rescue. We have found that dogs in foster homes are much more adoptable because they have been observed in a home setting. Dogs listed with Paws New England typically reside in various locations throughout the south (primarily Tennessee, Texas, and Arkansas) and New England (not necessarily in the state of Rhode Island). You will be notified by the adoption coordinator of the location of the dog you are interested in so you have the ability to decide whether to pursue adoption or not.

Dogs transported to New England are done so at a fee of $150.00 paid directly to the transporting company by Paws New England; no additional transport costs are responsibility of adopter. This fee is included in the adoption donation.

Adoption donations cover pre-adoption vet costs (including vaccinations, spay/neuter when age appropriate, and heartworm testing/treatment when necessary), a microchip, and transportation to New England if necessary.

Donations for our young, healthy puppies and dogs support their fellow canines of advanced age or suffering from injuries and abuse whose donations are reduced but whose veterinary costs are typically much higher. We appreciate your understanding that your dog will help others in need.

All known information about the animal is listed above. We do our best to give accurate information, but most of our dogs are rescues and do not come with a known history.

Paws New England abides by the dog importation regulations set forth in the states of MA, CT, NH and RI.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Adorable FELIPE is a 10 lb. 4-5 year-old chihuahua/terrier mix boy looking for a new furever home. He is losing his current home through no fault of his own. Felipe's person is in failing health and no longer able to care for him. He was very happy as a constant companion to his retired mom. To ease his transition, we would like to find Felipe a home where he has a similar setup to his previous home -- as an only dog in a quieter home. He is housebroken and walks well on a leash. He's been living in an apartment. If you'd like to meet this adorable boy, please fill out a foster-to-adopt application at
dreamhouserescue.org.

All of our fully-vetted adoptable dogs go to prospective homes for a one-week trial foster-to-adopt period to make sure the dog and home are the right fit before an adoption is finalized. We only adopt dogs into homes where all current pets are spayed/neutered and current on vaccines and heartworm and flea and tick prevention. We do check veterinary references to make sure adopters are compliant with standard veterinary care.

Murry was found as a stray by a kind citizen. He was very skinny and needed help! He joined Furry Kids and has been loving life in his foster home! He may have Dachshund in him but we do not know for sure.

Murry is Potty trained. He Sleeps all night with his foster human who is a teen and the foster Shiba dog. He gets along great with every one he meets! His nickname is Mr. Wiggles because he is just so happy and wiggly!

Murry has been, wormed, microchipped, and heartworm tested, and vaccinated. If you are interested in meeting/adopting one of them just fill out a application at www.furrykidsrefuge.org, click on the 'Adopt A Dog' icon and a dedicated volunteer will be in touch.
Furry Kids' Refuge is in need of good quality dog and puppy food with meat as the first ingredient. You can drop off donations at our weekly adoption events at the Lee's Summit Petco (1860 NW Chipman Road, Lee's Summit, MO), Saturdays only from Noon to 4:00 p.m. Donations are tax deductible as allowed by law.
Would you like to foster a Furry Kid? Furry Kids' Refuge will supply the food & vet care while you supply the basic house rules & love.......win-win for all!! Just visit our website http://www.furrykidsrefuge.org/category/fostering/ for more information. Thanks for your support!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.This guy is River! He is a four-year-old beagle, a chunky monkey, and he needs a home. Because River has demonstrated resource guarding of his food around both other dogs and children, we need to be very careful with his placement. River is neutered, micro chipped, current with rabies vaccine, and we will check him for heartworms and tickborne diseases.
